stefsched: I have a question, please.   Why do experts say it is better to have a 4/4 trumps than, let's say, 5/3 between dummy and hand, when you can create an extra trick (trump trick) with the imbalance?|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Sometimes 4/4 can be better than a 5/3 because it is easier to score extra trump tricks. For example, lets assume you have all high trumps in a 4/4 fit and you can maneuver two ruffs in one hand. Then you get six trump tricks: the four in the "long" hand, plus the two ruffs. With a 5/3 fit, you can establish your five-card suit and throw off losers.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|That is why sometimes it is better to play in a 4/4 fit rather than a 5/3 but not always, so be careful. The disadvantage is that if you get a 4/1 break for example, you are better off if you have five trumps in one hand. With a 4/4 fit, and a 4/1 break, the opponent has the same number of trumps as you. Whereas, with a 5/3 fit, you have one more, and that can often be crucial. The right answer to the 5/3 vs. 4/4 debate is not clear.|
